Pachin (VAL) 2025/07/15 14:31
‚¨áÔ∏èNot right now, but something we need to discuss‚¨áÔ∏è How should we proceed after Tunnel 6 opens? 1. All 3 ally players go for the cactus! I feel like this is a bit inefficient. I want to make sure I protect the cactus, but at the same time, not doing anything to the enemy is a bit tricky. Considering the information we have, if the red faction has the overall advantage, we also need to apply pressure with purple. 2. Cactus on 2 ally, purple on 1 ally. This was VAL's wilderness style last time. The alliance with the fewest players gathers buffs with purple, while the stronger 2 ally holds back the cactus. At some point, VAL headed for the cactus early on, and after successfully suppressing the wonder, they invaded purple as well, reducing the pressure on the cactus by appearing to be aggressive. I think this pattern will work again this time, but since the difference in strength between us and the enemy is still unclear, I think we should play it safe. In the cactus area, you can observe the enemy's movements and engage in 1:1 duels to clearly establish the difference in strength. You can also move forward while merging at 2-Ara and constantly maintain a 2:1 ratio. However, merging and advancing will slow down the gathering of buffs to secure the anthill. It's best to split up early, gather buffs, then watch the enemy's movements and decide where to meet up. The most important points in the cactus area that you must capture are the leaves and the port south of the cactus. The buffs north of the wonders consume a lot of power annually, so you should consider giving up. Based on the above, the 2-1 split follows: Pattern ‚ë°-1: DAR.VAL takes on the cactus, while MQT takes on the purple plan. DAR.VAL, with its larger number of players, firmly suppresses the cactus. MQT attacks the purple, but without pushing too hard, aiming to not give the enemy buffs and secure the anthill while advancing. ‚ë°-2 DAR.MQT with Cactus and VAL in Purple. The blue team coming into Purple is in 2-ara, and if they don't coordinate well, they might be crushed. If the enemy is aggressively pushing all the way to the Miraculous Lands and then comes in with 3-ara, we can switch DAR to Purple and win the 2:3 battle with sheer numbers. However, if we do do this, we should first secure Cactus, which is an advantageous position, and eliminate the enemy. If we can't win until then, we should retreat and conserve resources. ‚ë°-3 VAL.MQT with Cactus and DAR in Purple. The movement is the same as ‚ë°-2. In either case, the most important thing to be careful of is resource management. Running out of resources late in the game is unacceptable. It's important to understand the availability of logins for each ara and main faction between 8-16 UTC and check the resource numbers. There is still some time until the campsites are released, so during this time you'll want to keep track of the login status and resource amounts of players with a certain level of strength (for example, shooters with over 1 billion Mamo, and career and Gade players who can fight against users of that strength).

Pachin (VAL) 2025/07/15 16:01
(Reference data for required resources) In my case, the cost of treating a T11 shooter in Lost was... Treating 100,000 enemies required 2M of regenerative bacteria, 4.5M of meat, 2.9M of leaves, 1.5M of earth, 1.8M of sand, and 0.77M of oil. If regenerative bacteria production was 2.9M/h, that would amount to about 70M of regenerative bacteria per day. Using regenerative bacteria, the number of T11s that could be treated per day was 3.5 million. The resources required for this were 157.5M of meat, 101.5M of leaves, 52.5M of earth, 63M of sand, and 27M of oil. This is the amount consumed just for the bacteria recovered in a day. Add to that the consumption by using T9s, and the consumption becomes even more dramatic. If you currently have less than 1G of sand or oil, you need to be careful about how you fight, otherwise you risk running out of resources. Also, the number of healing time-saving items is important. I have about 5,000 hours' worth of healing time-saving items in stock, so I think I'll be fine. By the way, I spent over 2,000 hours in the last Wild West game. There may be many people who find this to be insufficient.

Pachin (VAL) 2025/08/05 7:58
@everyone , thank you for joining us late into the night last night. Starting today, our approach will change again, so I'll share my thoughts along with my previous instructions. Please note that my previous instructions and the explanations I'll give from now on are hindsight and will vary greatly depending on the enemy's behavior, the difference in strength, and the number of participants at any given time. It's difficult to provide the "explained in advance" that we discussed last night, and this decision was one of many possible responses, so please read with a full understanding. 1. First day of the Thorns Liberation (August 3rd) Our primary objective is to advance close to the enemy tunnel and control enemy movement in the Thorns area. Even if there are few members logged in during the day, it's important to set up towers as quickly as possible and suppress the enemy near the tunnel. The southern tunnel requires at least 20 towers to reach, making it impossible to blockade. This means that during our protection period on this day, the enemy team can move freely through the Thorns area. In this case, the enemy barely moved (or could barely move), but the next morning, there's a risk that the enemy will gather three enemies and surround one of the enemies or habitats, creating a 1:3 situation. Therefore, it's important to maximize your fungus and clay reserves on this day. If you neglect the tunnel secured by RED and they escape south, you'll waste even more clay that day. It's also a bad idea to waste fungus by fighting the enemy in a place like Purple, where you'll incur more damage. Based on this philosophy, "Ignore Purple for now. No fighting." The top priority is to "block the tunnel over Cactus and Purple." ‚ë° August 4th (Second Day of Thorns) This day is the phase where you must eliminate as many enemies as possible from Thorns and complete the takeover. Because the enemy barely moved this time, we were able to block the tunnel in one day (and in about three hours) and create a situation where the enemy towers in the Thorns area were left with only mobs. In this situation, as long as the tunnel is secured and the protection period begins, the enemy will be unable to operate within the thorn area. This is essentially a state of control, and as long as the tunnel can be defended, it can be used freely with low risk, even if fungus or clay is used freely. Additionally, depending on the number of enemies and allies, it may be possible to attempt an attack on the enemy camp beyond the tunnel. (Incidentally, at yesterday's VAL, 5-6 aces, no less than Chapi from DAR, were always available to participate.) Given this situation, we took measures to further ensure the tunnel's defense. This involved completely eliminating mobs. If you look next to the tunnel currently held by DAR, both KRG and RED are connected to the tunnel held by DAR. In this situation, for example, if RED and KRG launch a combined attack (about 50 people in total) during a time when DAR's participation is low (say, 15 people), isn't there a risk that the tunnel could be seized? If this had succeeded in eliminating the RED and KRG towers, the enemy would only be able to attack in a 1:1 situation, and even if their teammates were not well-positioned at the time, they would be able to hold out until their main force arrived. The same could be said for VAL. If the main force was absent and they were attacked simultaneously by MOB and KRG, there would still be the risk of losing the tunnel. Therefore, since many main forces were present and the KRG towers could be destroyed even with their own buffs, I believe destroying the MOB towers was an effective strategy. Of course, even if the tunnel were to be lost, it would be easy to wipe out the enemy again! You might be thinking, "VAL, you're being too scared!" However, if we were going to use clay for that purpose, it would be better to eliminate even small risks so that we could play with the enemy using purple or red clay (phase 3 that follows) without any worries, so I adopted this approach. Furthermore, yesterday's VAL advance showed that with a sufficient main force, a KRG of 5-6 can destroy the enemy tower in about an hour, regardless of the resistance. ‚ë¢As mentioned in ‚ë° today, the tunnel held by DAR carries the risk of being breached depending on the timing. During today's protection period, build one or two DAR towers on the thorny side of the tunnel to prevent the enemy from immediately building towers in the unlikely event that the tunnel cannot be fully defended. (This should likely reduce the enemy's fighting spirit.) If necessary, you can extend the VAL towers to that point. (This will further reduce the enemy's fighting spirit, making them think, "Oh no, we can't do this anymore.") The KRG is occupying the area in front of the tunnel, so the VAL side won't immediately be outnumbered 1:2, but they still have mob towers, so take the same measures. (More on this later.)
